            "content": "## Summary\n\nPolicy evaluation engine: combined RBAC/ABAC with **deny-overrides-allow**, versioned and logged decisions. Consumed by the config resolver (#46) and every tool/capability check.\n\n## Context\n\nSPEC.md §7.4–§7.5. Builds on the org/role model from #44. This is the \"policy before capability\" spine — a connector/model/skill is available only if effective policy allows it.\n\n## Design\n\n- `policies(id, scope_type, scope_id, effect, action, resource_type, resource_id, conditions_json, version)`\n- Evaluation: collect applicable policies across the scope chain, then **deny overrides allow**; a more-specific allow wins only when it does not conflict with a deny.\n- `PolicyService.check({ actor, action, resource, context }) -> Decision` returning effect + reason + matched policy IDs/versions; every decision is written to an audit log.\n- Approval semantics (`never_allowed`, `always_ask`, `ask_once_per_run|chat|project`, `auto_allow_readonly|low_risk`, `admin_only`) surfaced as part of the `Decision` (SPEC §7.5) for the run/tool layer to enforce later.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] deny overrides allow across the scope chain; decisions are deterministic and logged\n- [ ] policies are versioned; a decision records which policy versions applied\n- [ ] approval level returned alongside allow/deny\n- [ ] `check()` exercised by a stub tool-gate test\n\n## Requirements\n\n- #44 — identity, org units & roles (scope chain + actor roles)\n",
