            "content": "# #60 — Trusted tenant identity in apps/api (request auth)\n\n## Summary\n\nGive `apps/api` a **verified tenant identity per request**, derived only from the authenticated session — never from client input — and feed it into `TenantDbService.runAs(userId)` so RLS is engaged with a trusted tenant. This closes the IDOR that #61 mitigated by deleting the chat endpoints, and is the **hard prerequisite for #55** (the loop can't scope RLS without a trusted `userId`).\n\n## Key finding (corrects an earlier assumption)\n\n`apps/web` NextAuth is configured `session: { strategy: \"jwt\" }` (`app/(auth)/auth.ts`). With JWT sessions the session lives in an **encrypted cookie** (`authjs.session-token`), and the `sessions` table is **not** populated — so `apps/api` **cannot** validate by looking a token up in the shared `sessions` table. Identity must come from the JWT itself or from a web-minted assertion. (Earlier notes in the #54 spec / AGENTS that said \"validate against the sessions table\" are wrong and should be corrected.)\n\n## One open decision — identity source\n\nBoth give `apps/api` a trusted `userId`; they differ in coupling and deployment topology.\n\n- **(A) apps/api decodes the Auth.js session JWT.** The browser sends the `authjs.session-token` cookie to `apps/api`; a guard decodes/verifies it with the shared `AUTH_SECRET` (via `@auth/core/jwt` `decode`). Single token, one secret. Cost: couples `apps/api` to Auth.js's JWT/cookie format (breaks if Auth.js changes it), and the cookie must reach `apps/api` (same-site — i.e. both apps behind one reverse proxy / same domain).\n\n- **(B) apps/web BFF mints an internal identity token — recommended.** The browser only talks to `apps/web`. `apps/web` (which already runs `auth()` server-side) resolves the session → `userId`, mints a short-lived HS256 JWT `{ sub: userId, iat, exp: iat+~120s }` signed with a shared `INTERNAL_API_SECRET`, and forwards it to `apps/api` as `Authorization: Bearer …`. `apps/api`'s guard verifies that simple token. Decoupled from Auth.js internals, topology-agnostic (web forwards server-side, no cross-origin cookie), trivial guard. Cost: a second shared secret + a mint step in web.\n\nRecommend **B**: it matches api-first (web = thin BFF/UI, api = backend), keeps `apps/api` independent of Auth.js, and avoids cross-origin cookie fragility. The spec below assumes B; the guard contract is the same shape under A (only the verify step + token source change).\n\n## Design (assuming B)\n\n- **apps/web (mint):** a small server-side helper — given the `auth()` session, sign `{ sub: session.user.id }` (HS256, `INTERNAL_API_SECRET`, ~2 min expiry) and attach it to every `apps/api` call. No identity ever travels in the body/query/params.\n- **apps/api (verify):** a NestJS `SessionAuthGuard` (`CanActivate`) that reads the bearer token, verifies signature + expiry, extracts `sub` → `userId`, and attaches it to a **request-scoped identity** (e.g. `req.userId` / a `RequestContext`). Missing / malformed / bad-signature / expired → **401**, fail closed.\n- **Tie into #53:** all DB work runs inside `TenantDbService.runAs(req.userId, …)` using the **verified** id. `userId` is never accepted from the request payload (that was the #59 IDOR).\n- **Re-introduce endpoints behind the guard:** the chat routes removed in #61 come back, guard-protected and owner-scoped by the verified `userId`.\n- **Secret:** `INTERNAL_API_SECRET` shared via env in both apps (documented in `.env.example`); the app DB role stays non-superuser (RLS still the backstop).\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `SessionAuthGuard` verifies the internal token; **missing / malformed / forged / expired → 401** (fail closed).\n- [ ] Verified `userId` is attached to the request context and is the **only** source of tenant identity — never read from body/query/params.\n- [ ] DB access runs inside `TenantDbService.runAs(verifiedUserId, …)`; RLS is engaged with the trusted tenant.\n- [ ] `apps/web`