            "content": "# #60 — Trusted tenant identity in apps/api (revocable server-side sessions)\n\n## Summary\n\nGive `apps/api` a **verified, revocable tenant identity per request**, derived only from an authenticated server-side session — never from client input — and feed it into `TenantDbService.runAs(userId)` so RLS runs under a trusted tenant. Closes the IDOR #61 mitigated by deleting the chat endpoints; **hard prerequisite for #55**.\n\nPer the OWASP Session Management guidance, identity rests on a **revocable, server-side session with an opaque token**, not a stateless JWT.\n\n## Key finding (drives the whole design)\n\n- `apps/web` currently uses `session: { strategy: \"jwt\" }` — **forced**, because the **Credentials (email/password) provider requires JWT** in Auth.js (docs: *\"this provider requires JSON Web Tokens to be enabled for sessions\"*). The `sessions` table is configured (Drizzle adapter) but **unused**.\n- JWT sessions are **not revocable** (no server-side logout / \"sign out everywhere\" / breach revocation before expiry) — the OWASP concern Leo raised.\n- Therefore: achieving revocable server-side sessions means **replacing NextAuth's JWT session layer** with a server-side session store. We can't just flip `strategy: \"database\"` while Credentials is in use.\n\n## Scope — split into a precursor + the api bridge\n\n### Precursor (apps/web) — revocable server-side sessions  *(recommend its own issue, blocks this)*\nReplace the JWT session with an opaque, DB-backed session (finally using the `sessions` table):\n- On credential login: generate a high-entropy opaque token; store **only its hash** in `sessions` (token, `userId`, `createdAt`, `expiresAt`, `lastSeenAt`); set it as an **`HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax`** cookie.\n- Validate each request by DB lookup; enforce **absolute + idle expiry**; **rotate** the token on login/privilege change; **revoke** by deleting the row (logout, \"sign out everywhere\", admin/breach).\n- Keep NextAuth only for the credential *check* (password verify), or drop it for a minimal custom session layer — decided in that issue.\n\n### #60 proper (apps/api) — validate the session\n- A NestJS `SessionAuthGuard` reads the session token (cookie or `Authorization`), hashes it, **looks it up in the shared `sessions` table**, checks not-expired / not-revoked → `userId`. Missing / unknown / expired / revoked → **401, fail closed**.\n- Attach the verified `userId` to a request-scoped context; it is the **only** source of tenant identity (never body/query/params).\n- All DB work runs inside `TenantDbService.runAs(verifiedUserId, …)`; RLS engaged with the trusted, **revocable** tenant.\n- Re-introduce the chat endpoints removed in #61, guard-protected and owner-scoped by the verified id.\n\nThis makes revocation real end-to-end: deleting a `sessions` row instantly invalidates the user in **both** apps (web middleware + api guard) — impossible with the JWT.\n\n## OWASP alignment checklist\n- Opaque, high-entropy token; **stored hashed** at rest.\n- `HttpOnly` + `Secure` + `SameSite=Lax`; no token in URL/body/logs.\n- Server-side **absolute + idle** expiry; **rotation** on auth-state change; **revocation** on logout / sign-out-everywhere / breach.\n- Fail closed (deny on any doubt); identity never client-supplied.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- [ ] Web issues an opaque, hashed-at-rest, `HttpOnly/Secure/SameSite` session; supports logout + \"sign out everywhere\" (revocation).\n- [ ] `apps/api` `SessionAuthGuard` validates by `sessions` lookup; missing/unknown/expired/**revoked** → 401.\n- [ ] Verified `userId` is the sole tenant-identity source; DB access runs inside `runAs(verifiedUserId)`.\n- [ ] **Revocation test:** revoke a session → the next `apps/api` request returns 401 (proves non-JWT revocability).\n- [ ] **Cross-tenant negative test:** user A cannot read/write user B's chats; forged/absent token → 401; cross-tenant read = zero rows.\n- [ ] Re-introduced chat endpoints are gu