enforcement is impossible with the current schema.\n3. The spec's column list in parentheses contains `token` and `tokenHash` ambiguously — it must be clarified to `tokenHash` (the only thing stored) with the raw token never persisted.\n\n**Required before implementation:** A migration spec adding `token_hash text NOT NULL` (SHA-256 hex of the opaque token), `last_seen_at timestamptz`, `created_at timestamptz`, and deprecating the raw `session_token` PK in favour of `token_hash` as the lookup key. Without this migration, the guard cannot look up by hash and the \"hash at rest\" OWASP claim is false.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 2 — Token Crypto Primitives Unspecified\n\n**Severity: High**\n**Reference:** Spec §\"Precursor (apps/web)\" — \"generate a high-entropy opaque token\"\n\nThe spec does not name the CSPRNG or hash algorithm. These are security requirements, not implementation choices:\n\n- **Token generation must be:** `crypto.randomBytes(32)` (Node built-in, CSPRNG), encoded as base64url or hex → 256 bits of entropy. `uuid()` (122 effective bits, UUID v4) or `Math.random()` (deterministic, insecure) are common mistakes at this exact step.\n- **At-rest hash must be:** SHA-256 minimum. MD5 and SHA-1 are broken for this use case.\n- **Constant-time compare:** mostly moot here — validation is a `WHERE token_hash = $1` DB lookup (hash equality in SQL), not an application-level compare of secrets. But if any code path compares raw tokens in-memory (e.g., a cache or refresh path), it must use `crypto.timingSafeEqual()`.\n\nThe spec must name these. Leaving them to implementor discretion at an auth foundation layer is a security gap regardless of how capable the implementor is — it becomes untestable and un-auditable.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 3 — Revocability Is Contingent on the Deferred Precursor; Spec Overstates the Guarantee\n\n**Severity: High**\n**Reference:** Spec §\"This makes revocation real end-to-end\" and §\"Out of scope / deferred\"\n\nThe spec states: \"deleting a