be `enableCors({ origin: WEB_ORIGIN, credentials: true })` — `origin: '*'` with `credentials: true` is rejected by browsers per the CORS spec.\n- `apps/api/src/main.ts` currently has no `enableCors()` call at all.\n\n**Bearer token via `Authorization` header:**\n- If `Authorization` headers are logged by NestJS, nginx, or any infrastructure layer between client and API, the raw pre-image token appears in plaintext in logs. Since the DB stores only the hash, any log breach compromises all active sessions. The spec must require that `Authorization` header values are never logged, or that the Bearer token is itself a second-level derived value (less practical).\n- The spec does not specify which source (cookie vs. Authorization) takes precedence when both are present.\n\n**Required:** The spec must pin the topology (same-origin vs. cross-origin), specify CORS configuration for each case, and define guard input precedence. This is not an implementation detail — it controls whether `SameSite=Lax` is sufficient, whether CORS is required, and whether the cookie path works at all.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 5 — `GET /users/:id` and `GET /users/email/:email` Expose Password Hashes Without Authentication\n\n**Severity: High**\n**File:** `apps/api/src/users/users.controller.ts:9–19`\n\nThese endpoints are live in the codebase, require no authentication, and return the full `User` type:\n\n```typescript\n// users.controller.ts — no auth guard, no field exclusion\n@Get(':id')\nasync getUserById(@Param('id') id: string): Promise&lt;User | undefined&gt; {\n  return this.usersService.getUserById(id);  // returns User including password field\n}\n\n@Get('email/:email')\nasync getUserByEmail(@Param('email') email: string): Promise&lt;User | undefined&gt; {\n  return this.usersService.getUserByEmail(email);  // same\n}\n```\n\n`User` is `InferSelectModel&lt;typeof users&gt;` which includes `password: text('password')` (the bcrypt hash). Any caller with network access to `apps/api` can obtain the bcrypt hash of any user's password by email address, then run offline dictionary attacks.\n\nThis is a pre-existing issue the spec does not address. It is a hard blocker before `apps/api` is exposed to anything beyond a localhost dev process, which is the direction #60 explicitly moves toward. The spec's scope must include: (1) add auth guard to all user-facing `apps/api` endpoints, and (2) strip the `password` field from all `User` responses via a DTO or serialization interceptor.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 6 — IDOR Regression Path: `ChatsService` Takes `userId` as Plain Parameter\n\n**Severity: Medium**\n**Files:** `apps/api/src/chats/chats.service.ts`, Spec §\"Re-introduce the chat endpoints\"\n\nThe spec says to re-introduce the chat endpoints that were removed in #61 to close an IDOR. The `ChatsService` still accepts `userId` as a plain method argument. The spec's AC states \"Verified userId is the sole tenant-identity source\" but does not mandate the architectural pattern that makes this structurally enforced rather than a convention to remember.\n\nIf a future controller reads `userId` from a request body, query param, or path param and passes it to the service, that is the same IDOR as #61. The spec should mandate the `@CurrentUser()` decorator / request-scoped `AuthContext` injection pattern so the verified identity from the guard is the only value the service can receive — not a pattern any controller author can break by reading from `req.params`.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 7 — RLS Fail-Safe Confirmed; One Edge to Assert\n\n**Severity: Low (informational)**\n**Files:** `apps/api/src/db/schema/chats.ts:51–53`, `apps/api/src/db/tenant-db.service.ts:41–43`\n\nThe `current_setting('app.current_user_id', true)` second argument (`true` = missing-ok) is correct fail-safe behaviour: if `set_config` was never called (guard bypassed), `current_setting` returns NULL, and `owner_user_id = NULL` evaluates to NULL (not TRUE) under SQL three-valued logic — all rows are denied