            "content": "# #60 — Trusted tenant identity in apps/api (revocable server-side sessions)\n\n## Summary\n\nGive `apps/api` a **verified, revocable tenant identity per request**, derived only from an authenticated server-side session — never from client input — feeding `TenantDbService.runAs(userId)` so RLS runs under a trusted tenant. Closes the IDOR #61 mitigated by deleting the chat endpoints; **hard prerequisite for #55**. Identity rests on a **revocable, server-side session with an opaque token** (OWASP Session Management), not a stateless JWT.\n\nThis spec was security-reviewed; the requirements below (esp. R1–R4) are hard gates, not polish.\n\n## Why JWT today, and why it must change\n\n- `apps/web` uses `session: { strategy: \"jwt\" }` — **forced** by the Credentials provider (Auth.js: *\"this provider requires JSON Web Tokens to be enabled for sessions\"*). The `sessions` table exists (Drizzle adapter) but is **unused**.\n- JWT sessions are **not revocable** (no real logout / sign-out-everywhere / breach revocation before expiry).\n- So revocable server-side sessions require **replacing NextAuth's JWT session layer** with a DB-backed opaque-token session.\n\n## Ships as TWO atomic, co-dependent pieces\n\n**These must ship together.** Shipping the api guard while web still uses JWT yields a *false* revocation guarantee (a revoked DB row can't kill an in-flight JWT on the web side) — worse than today. (Security review F3.)\n\n### Precursor issue (apps/web) — revocable server-side sessions  *(separate issue, blocks #60)*\n### #60 (apps/api) — validate the session → trusted identity\n\n## Hard requirements (from security review)\n\n**R1 — Schema migration (F1).** The current `sessions` table (`session_token` raw PK, `user_id`, `expires`) cannot deliver the spec. Migration adds:\n- `token_hash text NOT NULL` — SHA-256 (hex) of the opaque token; **the lookup key**. The raw token is **never persisted**.\n- `created_at timestamptz NOT NULL DEFAULT now()`,