          "type": "user",
          "text": "Base directory for this skill: /home/leon0399/.claude/skills/iterative-review-refinement\n\n# Iterative Review Refinement\n\n## Overview\n\n**One reviewer is anecdote. Two parallel reviewers with independent defaults are signal. Convergence — not round count — is the stop condition.**\n\nDocuments that look right on first pass routinely contain factual errors, stale cross-references, and subtle logic gaps that a single careful read won't catch. The fix is not \"read more carefully\" — it's pressure-testing via independent reviewers, verifying each load-bearing finding against primary sources, and iterating until both reviewers stop finding substantive issues.\n\nThis is TDD for documents. The draft is production code. Reviewers are tests. Convergence is green.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Finished initial draft of a design memo, research report, plan, RFC, analysis, or technical spec\n- Document will inform load-bearing decisions or land in a PR\n- Errors are costly to find later (after merge, after implementation starts, after stakeholders rely on it)\n- You're tempted to ship after one read-through because \"it looks right\"\n\n**Don't use for:**\n- Scratch notes, single-paragraph comments, ephemeral text\n- Documents already gated by mandatory human review with equivalent rigor\n- Trivial fixes where review overhead exceeds value\n- Code: use code-review skills instead (this is for prose deliverables)\n\n## Specialist subagents\n\nTwo user-level specialists are available and SHOULD be preferred over `general-purpose`:\n\n- **`iterative-review-reviewer`** (cyan) — primary GP-side reviewer for the loop. Inherits this skill's methodology, audit-surface checklist, output format, anti-rationalization rule, and primary-source verification mandates. Per-round prompt shrinks to the round delta.\n- **`adversarial-reviewer-fallback`** (red) — hostile substitute when `plugin:codex:adversarial-review` is unavailable (usage limit, tool failure). Defaults to literal readings, parallel-callout focus, and Codex-class blind-spot coverage.\n\nWhen dispatching parallel reviewers, the canonical pair is **`plugin:codex:adversarial-review` + `iterative-review-reviewer`**. Fallback pair when Codex is down: **`iterative-review-reviewer` + `adversarial-reviewer-fallback`**. Don't pair two `general-purpose` agents — they share blind spots.\n\n### Dispatch examples\n\nCanonical pair — Codex + GP-side specialist (default when Codex is available). Dispatch BOTH in a single message with parallel tool calls:\n\n```typescript\nBash({\n  command: `node \"$CODEX_COMPANION_PATH\" adversarial-review \"--background \\\"<prompt — see 'Codex prompting tactics' subsection below for required framing>\\\"\"`,\n  description: \"Codex round N\",\n  run_in_background: true\n})\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"iterative-review-reviewer\",\n  description: \"Round N verification\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. v<N-1>→v<N> delta: <fixes applied this round>. Prior-round findings: <link or 'see revision-history lines X-Y'>. Optional focus: <surfaces to probe>.\"\n})\n```\n\nFallback pair — when Codex is unavailable (usage limit, transient failure). Dispatch both specialists in parallel:\n\n```typescript\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"iterative-review-reviewer\",\n  description: \"Round N verification\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. v<N-1>→v<N> delta: <fixes applied this round>.\"\n})\nAgent({\n  subagent_type: \"adversarial-reviewer-fallback\",\n  description: \"Round N hostile probe\",\n  prompt: \"Doc: <abs-path>. Round N. Primary reviewer dispatched in parallel. Hostile-probe focus: <sites the primary might rationalize / surfaces Codex would catch>.\"\n})\n```\n\nThe fallback pair is weaker than Codex + specialist because both agents share Claude's blind spots — but stronger than a single reviewer because the hostile-framing default produces orthogonal findings on the same model.\n\nPer-round prompt shrinks from ~1,500 words (when methodology lives in the prompt) to ~150-300 words (when methodology lives in the agents' system prompts). If you find yourself re-pasting the audit-surface checklist or output format into per-round prompts, the agent system prompts need tightening — the methodology should ride on the agent, not the prompt.\n\n## Core Loop\n\n```\n1. Draft vN exists, ready for adversarial review\n       │\n       ▼\n2. Dispatch ≥2 INDEPENDENT reviewers in PARALLEL\n   - Codex via plugin:codex:adversarial-review (primary)\n   - iterative-review-reviewer specialist (GP-side)\n   - adversarial-reviewer-fallback if Codex unavailable\n       │\n       ▼\n3. Synthesize findings: dedupe across reviewers, classify P0 / P1 / P2\n       │\n       ▼\n4. INDEPENDENTLY VERIFY each load-bearing finding against primary sources\n   (do NOT trust the reviewer's assertion — check it yourself)\n       │\n       ▼\n5. Apply verified fixes → bump version (vN → vN+1) → write revision-history entry\n       │\n       ▼\n6. Converged?  ── no ──▶ back to step 2\n                  │\n                 yes\n                  ▼\n               ship\n```\n\n## Briefing the Reviewers\n\nReviewers default to thin context. Parallel reviewers regress to single-reviewer signal if both are briefed poorly. Brief each one explicitly:\n\n- **Paste prior-round findings verbatim** so the new round doesn't re-flag already-fixed issues\n- **Name files with full absolute or repo-relative paths** — don't make reviewers grep\n- **For gitignored targets, drop `--base` flags** (some review tools bail on gitignored content otherwise)\n- **Tell general-purpose agents to use the project runtime** (e.g. `uv run python3`, `bun run`) for arithmetic and code checks — not the global interpreter\n- **State the document's purpose and load-bearing claims**: what decisions does it gate, what's already been verified, what's known to be uncertain\n- **List the supporting artifacts** (e.g. `sources.jsonl`, `bibliography.bib`, companion notebooks) and ask reviewers to check consistency across them\n\nA thin brief produces thin findings.\n\n### Exploit reviewer blind spots\n\nCodex and general-purpose agents have systematically different failure modes — observed across 40+ rounds of split-decision findings:\n\n- **General-purpose agents are strong at:** arithmetic audits, dataclass-field consistency, primary-source verification when given the right tool flags, exhaustive grep-driven sweeps.\n- **General-purpose agents miss:** parallel-spec-contract drift (the same fix not propagated to all sites), diagnostic-vs-production parity, contradictions they rationalize away (\"this prose is describing X-from-another-angle so it doesn't contradict the new fix\").\n- **Codex is strong at:** parallel-callout detection, contract-drift across module boundaries, hostile probes of the rewrite that just landed, catching reviewer rationalizations.\n- **Codex misses:** subtle arithmetic when its tool-call flags fetch incomplete data (`gh issue view --json body` misses comments; `git diff` misses gitignored files; targeted grep can miss content past read-window).\n\nDispatch both, every round. A single-reviewer \"converged\" verdict is unreliable: ~⅓ of rounds in long iterations have split decisions where one reviewer's miss would have shipped a load-bearing bug.\n\n### Reviewer-tool gotchas to flag in the brief\n\n- **GitHub issue cites:** if a memo references a GitHub issue's body, brief reviewers to use `gh issue view N --comments` (NOT `--json body`). A common bug pattern is \"claim X is per issue N's recent comment\"; if a reviewer fetches only the body, they will report the cite as factually wrong when it's actually accurate.\n- **`git diff` on gitignored targets:** force reviewers to read the target file directly via `cat`/`nl -ba`/`Read`. Some review tools default to `git diff <base>...HEAD` and silently skip gitignored content, returning a \"no diff to review\" false-positive.\n- **Truncated tool output:** large files read via `se