a second general-purpose subagent with the hostile-find-what-Codex-would-find framing (see \"Reviewer steering tactics\" above). Don't ship on a single reviewer.\n6. **Codex sandbox is read-only.** Codex can't write files, even if the prompt asks. Useful for adversarial verification (the reviewer can't accidentally apply a fix), but flag if the brief contains write actions — Codex will report inability to act rather than a content finding.\n\n## Verify Before Fix\n\nA reviewer pointing at a \"bug\" can be:\n- **Right** → apply the fix\n- **Wrong about the primary source** → cite back, don't apply, document the disagreement\n- **Right about the symptom but wrong about the cause** → apply a different fix targeted at the actual cause\n\n**Always verify load-bearing findings against primary sources before changing the document.** Especially:\n- Version numbers, arXiv IDs, DOI strings, paper titles, author lists\n- File paths, function names, API signatures, deprecation status\n- Units, sign conventions, coordinate frames, axis orientations\n- Numeric values, equation coefficients, table entries\n\nUse WebFetch on the abstract page. Grep the repo. Run the snippet under the project runtime. Don't apply a fix because a reviewer asserted it confidently — reviewers (including AI agents) hallucinate.\n\n## Audit surfaces — where bugs hide\n\nA normative spec fix in long-form prose often fails to propagate to parallel surfaces. Every spec-block fix needs a global grep + sweep of ALL these surfaces, not just the named fix site. The list grows monotonically as a loop proceeds — track new surface classes when they appear:\n\n1. **Equation prose** (math definitions in scientific notation)\n2. **Standalone math blocks** (rendered LaTeX-style formulas — frequently lag the prose paragraph above them)\n3. **Algorithm-step pseudocode** (imperative implementation steps that USE the equations)\n4. **Diagnostic / sanity-check code blocks** (helper functions; must match production selection-and-reduction logic exactly)\n5. **Worked-example narrative** (illustrative tables; \"the contribution is from the closest arm\" can survive after the equation prose was corrected to \"argmax(g_i)\")\n6. **Test brackets / asserted-field names** (the field the test asserts on must match the production-path field)\n7. **Recommendation prose** (top-of-doc summary; often the first thing readers see, and the last thing authors update)\n8. **Helper / dataclass docstrings** (return values, field semantics, parameter ordering)\n9. **Pedagogical caveats** (\"note that under v5's convention...\" — version-stamped notes rot)\n10. **Load-bearing constraint callouts** (arm-radius domain, clamp safety floors)\n11. **Derivation paragraphs** (paragraphs that USE parameters to compute bounds: N_LOS, memory, performance gates) — distinct from #1 because they CONSUME parameters\n12. **Narrative-justification paragraphs** (\"X is acceptable because Y\") — distinct from #11 because these don't derive, they only argue\n13. **Compact summary tables** (one-cell restatements of long-form prose — drift HERE persists even after the prose is corrected, because table-row revisions are batched separately from prose revisions and reviewer attention often slides past the table when the prose looks right)\n\nWhen fixing a normative claim, before declaring the fix complete, run `rg` for the corrected token across the whole document. Re-check every match against the surface class. If any class is missing from the grep result but plausibly affected, sweep that surface manually.\n\n### Arithmetic vs justification — audit both separately\n\nClasses #11 (derivation paragraphs) and #12 (narrative-justification paragraphs) are independently auditable. A 14-point arithmetic audit can pass cleanly (every numeric value computes correctly) while justification paragraphs still drift (the REASON given for choosing a number references stale premises). Don't treat them as the same audit.\n\nEmpirically: in obser