          "input": {
            "content": "## v0.2: Foundations & durable runs\n\nThe keystone milestone. It establishes the **governance spine** (identity, policy, config resolution) and the **durable run pipeline** that every later milestone plugs into.\n\nSee SPEC.md §6–§9 and §24, and ROADMAP.md.\n\n### Architecture overview\n\nTwo things land here:\n\n1. **Governance spine** — users/orgs/memberships (#44) → RBAC deny-policy (#45) → a config resolver that snapshots effective config per run (#46).\n2. **Durable runs** — pg-boss queue on Postgres (#47) → the API only stores + enqueues while a worker runs the agent loop and appends to an append-only run-event store (#48) → clients replay events over SSE and survive refresh (#49) → the agent/LangGraph layer moves from `apps/web` into that worker (#50).\n\nDurable state lives in Postgres (`runs` + `run_events`); LangGraph is the executor, not the source of truth. Postgres-first throughout — no Redis or broker (SPEC §24.0).\n\n### Key design decisions\n\n- The API thread does no agent work — validate / store / enqueue / return only (SPEC §9.5).\n- The run-event store is append-only and cursor-replayable; the UI is a subscriber, not a state holder.\n- Config is resolved once and snapshotted per run for reproducibility and audit (SPEC §6.4).\n- Deny overrides allow; policy gates capabilities before they are ever available (SPEC §7.4).\n- Queue, cache, and scheduler are Postgres (pg-boss), behind a swappable interface (SPEC §23.4, §24.0).\n\n### Layer 1: Foundation (independent)\n\n- [ ] #44 — feat(api): identity, nested org units & memberships\n- [ ] #47 — feat(infra): pg-boss queue + scheduler on Postgres\n\n### Layer 2: Governance\n\n- [ ] #45 — feat(api): RBAC + deny-policy engine (requires #44)\n- [ ] #46 — feat(api): config resolver with per-run config snapshots (requires #44, #45)\n\n### Layer 3: Run pipeline\n\n- [ ] #48 — feat(api): durable run pipeline (requires #46, #47)\n\n### Layer 4: Surface & migration\n\n- [ ] #49 — feat(web): refresh-safe SSE run-event replay (requires #48)\n- [ ] #50 — refactor(api): move agent/LangGraph layer from web into the worker (requires #48)\n\n### Dependency graph\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n    I44[\"#44 identity / orgs\"]\n    Q47[\"#47 pg-boss queue\"]\n    R45[\"#45 RBAC + deny\"]\n    C46[\"#46 config resolver\"]\n    P48[\"#48 run pipeline\"]\n    S49[\"#49 SSE replay\"]\n    M50[\"#50 agent → worker\"]\n\n    I44 --> R45 --> C46\n    I44 --> C46\n    C46 --> P48\n    Q47 --> P48\n    P48 --> S49\n    P48 --> M50\n```\n\n### Success criteria\n\n- A user message creates a durable run processed by a worker, not the HTTP thread.\n- Refreshing the page mid-run restores progress from persisted events.\n- Effective config is snapshotted on each run and inspectable.\n- A denied capability is unavailable regardless of any lower-scope allow.\n- The agent loop runs in the worker; `apps/web` only calls the run API.\n\n### Start points (unblocked)\n\n**#44** (identity) and **#47** (pg-boss) — independent, can begin in parallel.\n",
