          "text": "Good instinct — model sessions as a resource and let HTTP verbs do the work, rather than RPC-style `/logout-all`. Resource-oriented `/auth/v1`:\n\n| Action | Endpoint |\n|---|---|\n| Log in (create session) | `POST /auth/v1/sessions` |\n| Who am I | `GET /auth/v1/me` |\n| List my active sessions (for the devices UI) | `GET /auth/v1/sessions` |\n| Log out (this session) | `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current` |\n| Revoke one device | `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/{id}` |\n| **Sign out everywhere** | `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions` |\n\nSo `/logout-all` and `/login` as verbs go away. My recommendations on the two debatable bits:\n\n1. **\"Sign out everywhere\" → `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions`** (collection delete), not `/sessions/all`. The bare collection-delete is the RESTfully-pure form, and the usual footgun (accidental mass wipe) doesn't apply here because the collection is **inherently scoped to the authenticated caller** — it can only ever delete *your own* sessions. `/all` is a magic pseudo-id that buys nothing. I'd skip it.\n2. Add **`DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/others`** for the more common UX — \"log out *other* devices, keep me signed in here.\" Most \"sign out everywhere\" buttons actually mean this. Cheap, and it reads cleanly as \"delete the others.\"\n\nOne judgment call worth flagging: **login as `POST /auth/v1/sessions`** is consistent and resource-pure (the session is the thing you create). The alternative — keeping `POST /auth/v1/login` as an explicit auth verb — is also common, on the argument that authentication isn't plain CRUD. I lean `POST /sessions` for consistency with the rest of the resource, but it's the one place I'd accept the RPC verb if you prefer it.\n\nIf that surface looks right (with `DELETE /sessions` for everywhere + `/sessions/others`, and `POST /sessions` for login), I'll lock it and write the whole architecture — boundary, the `/auth/v1` + `/api/v1` split, sessions-as-resource — into **SPEC.md**, then realign the issues to mat