th, resource for listing | [Stytch Sessions](https://stytch.com/docs/api/sessions) (JS-rendered; data from public docs) |\n| **Clerk** | Via hosted UI or Clerk-managed flows; backend: `POST /v1/client/sign_ins` | `DELETE /v1/client/sessions/{sessionId}/revoke` | `DELETE /v1/users/{userId}/sessions` (admin revoke all) | `GET /v1/sessions?user_id={id}` (Backend API) | `POST /v1/sessions/{sessionId}/revoke` | Resource for sessions; revoke via POST or DELETE | [Clerk Backend API](https://clerk.com/docs/reference/backend-api/tag/sessions) |\n| **Supabase (GoTrue)** | `POST /auth/v1/token?grant_type=password` | `POST /auth/v1/logout` + scope param | `POST /auth/v1/logout` (scope=`global`, default) | no direct user-facing list endpoint (admin: `GET /auth/v1/admin/users/{id}/sessions`) | `POST /auth/v1/logout` with scope=`others` (keeps current) | RPC-ish for auth; admin resource for user management | [Supabase signOut](https://supabase.com/docs/reference/javascript/auth-signout), [Supabase Sessions Guide](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/auth/sessions) |\n| **Firebase Auth** | Client SDK; Admin SDK: `createCustomToken()` / `verifyIdToken()` — no REST login endpoint; uses token verification model | Admin: `revokeRefreshTokens(uid)` — no HTTP DELETE endpoint; event-driven | `revokeRefreshTokens(uid)` — invalidates all tokens for user | No list endpoint | No per-session revoke | JWT-centric; revocation is all-or-nothing per user | [Firebase manage-sessions](https://firebase.google.com/docs/auth/admin/manage-sessions) |\n| **AWS Cognito** | `POST /` (AWS API protocol) `InitiateAuth` action | `GlobalSignOut` action (RPC via POST, Cognito API protocol) | `GlobalSignOut` (invalidates all tokens for the calling user) | No public list-sessions endpoint | `RevokeToken` (specific refresh token only) | AWS JSON-RPC protocol, no REST resource model | [Cognito access token docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cognito/latest/developerguide/) |\n| **Ory Kratos** | Via flow: `GET /self-service/login/browser` → submit → session issued | `DELETE /sessions/{id}` (specific) | `DELETE /sessions` (my other sessions, excluding current) | `GET /sessions` (listMySessions); admin: `GET /admin/sessions` | `DELETE /sessions/{id}` | **True resource model** for sessions | [Ory Kratos OpenAPI spec](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ory/kratos/master/spec/api.json) |\n| **Keycloak** | OIDC: `POST /realms/{realm}/protocol/openid-connect/token` | Admin REST: `DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/sessions/{session}` | `DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/users/{id}/sessions` (all) | `GET /admin/realms/{realm}/users/{id}/sessions` | `DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/sessions/{session}` | **Resource model** on admin side; OIDC on auth side | [Keycloak Admin REST API](https://www.keycloak.org/docs-api/latest/rest-api/index.html) |\n| **FusionAuth** | `POST /api/login` (explicit RPC) | `POST /api/logout` (with refresh token; `global=true` revokes all) | `DELETE /api/jwt/refresh?userId={id}` (admin; revoke all tokens) | No list-sessions endpoint (user-facing) | `DELETE /api/jwt/refresh/{token}` (specific token) | RPC verbs; no session resource | [FusionAuth Logout Guide](https://fusionauth.io/docs/lifecycle/authenticate-users/logout-session-management) |\n| **Better-Auth** | `POST /api/auth/sign-in/email` (RPC; from source: `sign-in.ts` method POST) | `POST /api/auth/sign-out` | `POST /api/auth/revoke-sessions` (all); `POST /api/auth/revoke-other-sessions` | `GET /api/auth/list-sessions` (multi-session plugin) | `POST /api/auth/revoke-session` (with token/sessionId) | RPC verbs throughout | [Better Auth source](https://github.com/better-auth/better-auth/tree/main/packages/better-auth/src/api/routes) |\n| **OWASP** | N/A | Recommends regenerating session ID on any privilege change; HttpOnly+Secure cookies | Recommends providing \"invalidate all sessions\" as user control | Recommends listing active sessions with device metadata | Recommends `DELETE` semantics with proper CSRF protection | Resource model preferred where REST principles apply | [OWASP Session Mgmt Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html) |\n\n---\n\n### Question-by-Question Analysis\n\n---\n\n#### Q1. Sessions as a resource vs RPC verbs\n\n**Prevailing practice: split, trending toward resource for session objects, RPC for auth flows.**\n\nThe market is genuinely split but follows a recognizable pattern:\n\n- **Auth flows (login itself)** — almost universally RPC-verb style: `POST /oauth/token` (Auth0, Supabase/GoTrue, Okta OIDC), `POST /api/login` (FusionAuth), `POST /v1/passwords/authenticate` (Stytch), `createAuthEndpoint` POST to `/api/auth/sign-in/*` (Better Auth). Only Ory Kratos treats login as a session-creation flow that ends with a session object being assigned — but even it routes through self-service flow URLs, not `POST /sessions`.\n- **Session management (post-login)** — resource-oriented is the clear winner here: Ory Kratos (`GET/DELETE /sessions`, `DELETE /sessions/{id}`), Okta (`GET/DELETE /api/v1/sessions/{id}`), Keycloak (`GET/DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/sessions/{id}`), Clerk (`GET /v1/sessions`, `DELETE /v1/sessions/{id}`). Auth0's Management API also models it this way with `GET/DELETE /api/v2/users/{id}/sessions`.\n- **RPC holdouts for everything**: FusionAuth (`POST /api/logout`), Better Auth (all POST verbs), Supabase (POST for logout), Stytch (POST for revoke).\n\n**Verdict**: The split is clean by *operation type*. Auth initiation is RPC everywhere. Session *object management* is resource-oriented in all the more mature/infrastructure-grade systems (Ory, Okta, Keycloak, Clerk, Auth0 Management).\n\n**Recommendation for your `/auth/v1`**: Use `POST /auth/v1/sessions` for login (creates a session), `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current` for logout, `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/{id}` for revoke-specific. This is what Ory Kratos does and what Auth0 and Okta do in their management planes. It's RESTfully consistent, mobile-API-friendly, and OpenAPI-describable without ambiguity. The RPC verb (`POST /login`) is fine for compatibility with OAuth2/OIDC flows but not for a first-party API you control.\n\n---\n\n#### Q2. \"Sign out everywhere\" / revoke-all\n\n**Prevailing practice: no consensus on the exact URL, but the semantics are universal — and \"others\" is the safer default.**\n\n| Product | How they express revoke-all |\n|---|---|\n| Ory Kratos | `DELETE /sessions` (deletes **other** sessions, not current) |\n| Okta | `DELETE /api/v1/users/{userId}/sessions` (admin; kills all including current) |\n| Keycloak | `DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/users/{id}/sessions` (admin; kills all) |\n| Clerk | `DELETE /v1/users/{userId}/sessions` (admin backend API) |\n| Supabase | `POST /auth/v1/logout` with `scope: 'global'` (kills all) or `scope: 'others'` (kills non-current) |\n| FusionAuth | `POST /api/logout?global=true` or `DELETE /api/jwt/refresh?userId=` |\n| Firebase | `revokeRefreshTokens(uid)` (all tokens, no per-session targeting) |\n| Better Auth | `POST /api/auth/revoke-sessions` (all) + `POST /api/auth/revoke-other-sessions` |\n| AWS Cognito | `GlobalSignOut` action (calling user only, all tokens) |\n\nThe most nuanced products (Supabase, Ory Kratos, Better Auth) distinguish:\n- **Revoke all including current** — sign out everywhere completely\n- **Revoke all others** — keep current session active (Supabase `scope: 'others'`, Ory `DELETE /sessions`, Better Auth `revoke-other-sessions`)\n\nThe \"keep current\" variant is the more UX-friendly option for a \"security devices\" page (the user is signed in and wants to kick others out without re-logging in).\n\n**Recommendation**: Expose both. `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions` = revoke all except current. Require explicit `?include_current=true` query parameter (or a separate action `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions?scope=all`) to nuke everything including the caller's session. Ory's pattern of \"DELETE /sessions = delete others\" is the safest default.\n\n---\n\n#### Q3. Log out current vs specific device / list sessions\n\n**Clear best practice: resource model with `current` alias.**\n\n- Ory Kratos: `DELETE /sessions/{id}` (specific), `DELETE /sessions` (all others), `GET /sessions` (list mine), `GET /sessions/whoami` (current)\n- Okta: `GET /api/v1/sessions/me` (current), `DELETE /api/v1/sessions/me` (logout current), `DELETE /api/v1/sessions/{sessionId}` (specific)\n- Keycloak Admin: `GET /admin/realms/{realm}/users/{id}/sessions` (list), `DELETE /admin/realms/{realm}/sessions/{session}` (specific)\n- Clerk: `GET /v1/sessions?user_id=` (list), `POST /v1/sessions/{id}/revoke` (specific)\n- Better Auth (multi-session plugin): `/multi-session/list-device-sessions` endpoint for listing\n\nThe `current` alias is used by Okta explicitly (`/sessions/me`), avoids requiring the client to know its own session ID (which it doesn't know if the token is opaque and sent via cookie).\n\n**Recommendation**:\n```\nGET    /auth/v1/sessions            — list all my sessions (paginated, includes device metadata)\nGET    /auth/v1/sessions/current    — get current session details\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current    — log out current session (= your \"logout\" action)\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions/{id}       — revoke a specific other session\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions            — revoke all other sessions (keep current)\n```\nThis exactly mirrors Ory Kratos + Okta and is strongly OWASP-aligned. The OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet explicitly recommends providing users a session listing with device metadata and the ability to revoke individual sessions.\n\n---\n\n#### Q4. Login as `POST /sessions` vs `POST /login`\n\n**Consensus: RPC verbs (`/token`, `/login`, `/sign-in`) dominate for login itself.**\n\nDespite the theoretical REST purity of `POST /sessions` = \"create a session\", almost no real-world system does this for login. The reasons:\n\n1. **OAuth2/OIDC conventions** (used by Auth0, Okta, Supabase, Cognito, Keycloak on their public auth surface) mandate `POST /oauth2/token`. Deviating from this breaks compatibility with standard OAuth2 clients and creates friction.\n2. **Semantics bleed**: Login isn't just session creation — it involves credential verification, MFA challenges, and may return an intermediate state (e.g., \"MFA required\"). This doesn't map cleanly to \"201 Created\".\n3. **Adoption**: Ory Kratos (the most opinionated resource-model system) still routes login through self-service flows (`/self-service/login/*`), not `POST /sessions`. FusionAuth uses `POST /api/login`. Better Auth uses `POST /api/auth/sign-in/email`. Stytch uses method-specific POSTs.\n\n**`POST /sessions` exists nowhere as the primary login endpoint in production systems.**\n\nNotable dissent: some academic API design guides recommend it for purity. It's theoretically sound.\n\n**Recommendation**: Use `POST /auth/v1/sessions` for your first-party API (you control both sides, no OIDC compatibility requirement for mobile app). The symmetry with `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current` is cleaner than splitting into `/login` + session resource. However, if you ever plan OAuth2 compatibility for third-party clients, expose `POST /auth/v1/token` as an alias. The key thing: since you're building a first-party API with opaque tokens, `POST /sessions` is defensible and internally consistent.\n\nConfidence: **moderate** — this is a genuine design tradeoff where reasonable engineers disagree.\n\n---\n\n#### Q5. Separate versioning of auth vs main API (`/auth/v1` + `/api/v1`)\n\n**Recognized pattern, explicitly used by several leading platforms.**\n\nEvidence:\n- **Supabase/GoTrue**: `/auth/v1/*` for auth, `/rest/v1/*` for data API — completely separate version lines. This is their production architecture. ([Source](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/auth/sessions))\n- **Okta**: `/api/v1/sessions`, `/api/v1/users` (same prefix but distinct resource families); OIDC lives under `/oauth2/v1/` — functionally separate versioning for OAuth vs management.\n- **Auth0**: `/oauth/token` vs `/api/v2/users` — auth and management are independently versioned paths.\n- **Clerk**: Backend API `/v1/sessions`, Frontend API at a different base.\n- **Ory Kratos**: `/sessions/*` (frontend API) vs `/admin/sessions/*` (admin API) — effectively separate versioning planes.\n- **Keycloak**: OIDC at `/realms/{realm}/protocol/openid-connect/*` vs admin at `/admin/realms/{realm}/*`.\n\n**Pros of separate `/auth/v1` + `/api/v1`**:\n- Auth endpoints have different security posture (no auth token needed for login, different rate limits, different CORS policy for mobile vs web)\n- Can evolve independently — bumping `/api/v2` doesn't require re-testing auth flows\n- Cleaner gateway/middleware routing (auth bypass for `/auth/*`, full auth middleware for `/api/*`)\n\n**Cons**:\n- Slightly more surface to document\n- Some auth-adjacent endpoints (e.g., password reset, MFA enrollment) blur the line\n\n**Recommendation**: Your planned `/auth/v1` + `/api/v1` split is correct and strongly supported by real-world evidence. Supabase's architecture is the closest match to your stack and they do exactly this. Keep auth-specific endpoints (sessions, password reset, email verification, MFA) under `/auth/v1` and domain resources (chats, models, etc.) under `/api/v1`.\n\n---\n\n#### Q6. Web (cookie) + mobile (Bearer) on one session API\n\n**Clear pattern: same opaque token, different transport.**\n\nThis is the most well-documented dual-transport pattern in the industry:\n\n**Ory Kratos** is the canonical reference: They explicitly document two session formats from a single auth system:\n- Browser: Ory Session Cookie (set automatically, HttpOnly, `Set-Cookie` on login)\n- Mobile/native: Ory Session Token (returned in response body, stored by client, sent as `X-Session-Token` header or `Authorization: Bearer`)\n\nBoth resolve to the same session object in the backend. The token IS the session identifier in both cases — just different transport. Ory docs: \"For security reasons, you can't break the isolation between cookies and session tokens.\" (Same session cannot be used in both modes simultaneously — one session = one transport.) [Source: Ory Kratos sessions overview](https://ory.sh/docs/kratos/session-management/overview)\n\n**Better Auth**: Supports cookie-based and Bearer token auth simultaneously; the session token is the same opaque identifier, transported differently.\n\n**Supabase**: Returns a JWT + refresh token on login. Browser clients store in `localStorage` (or httpOnly cookie in server-side flows); mobile clients store in secure storage and send as Bearer. Same token structure, different transport.\n\n**OWASP guidance**: HttpOnly cookie is mandatory for browser clients (prevents XSS theft); Bearer token in Authorization header is standard for native clients. Both require TLS. Session ID entropy minimum: 64 bits. ([OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html))\n\n**FusionAuth**: Explicitly supports both cookie mode (HttpOnly `access_token` + `refresh_token` cookies) and Bearer token mode for the same API. Set via configuration.\n\n**Recommendation for your architecture**:\n- Login response body: always return the opaque session token (for mobile to store)\n- Login response also sets: `Set-Cookie: session=&lt;token&gt;; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict` (for web BFF)\n- Authenticate requests by checking `Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;` first, then fall back to cookie (Ory's pattern)\n- The NestJS guard checks both transports against the same session lookup: `hash(token)` → DB\n- Mobile sends `Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;`; web BFF forwards the cookie (since it's a BFF, the Next.js server-side code reads the cookie and optionally re-forwards as Bearer to NestJS, or NestJS accepts cookies directly)\n- Do NOT share a session between cookie and Bearer transport for the same session — Ory's isolation rule is a security control, not just a UX decision\n\n---\n\n### Flags on Your Current Direction\n\n**Strongly supported by evidence**:\n- Separate `/auth/v1` + `/api/v1` versioning — Supabase, Auth0, Okta, Clerk all do this\n- `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current` for logout — Okta (`DELETE /sessions/me`), Ory (`DELETE /sessions/{id}`)\n- `GET /auth/v1/sessions` for list — Ory, Okta, Keycloak, Clerk all have this\n- `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions/{id}` for revoke-specific — universal in the resource-model systems\n- Opaque token hashed at rest + server-side revocable — OWASP-aligned; Ory Kratos, Better Auth, Clerk all use this model\n\n**Needs nuance**:\n- `DELETE /auth/v1/sessions` meaning \"revoke all\" — **Ory Kratos means \"revoke all others\" (not current)**. This is the right semantic. Make sure your implementation matches: \"revoke all\" the collection endpoint means all except the one making the request. Require an explicit flag/path for nuking current too.\n- `POST /auth/v1/sessions` for login — not contradicted by evidence, but not widely adopted. The risk is developer confusion (\"is this creating a session or authenticating?\"). Mitigate with good docs and clear error responses (400 with specific codes for wrong credentials, 403 for locked, etc.).\n\n**Potential gap — not yet addressed**:\n- Session listing needs device metadata (user-agent, IP, last-used-at, created-at) to be useful for a devices UI. Ory Kratos, Okta, and Clerk all return this. Plan the schema now.\n- The OWASP cheat sheet recommends session fixation protection (regenerate session ID on privilege elevation) — ensure your implementation regenerates the token on email/password change, role upgrade, etc.\n\n---\n\n### Recommended `/auth/v1` Endpoint List\n\n```\nPOST   /auth/v1/sessions                    Login (creates session; returns token in body + Set-Cookie)\nGET    /auth/v1/sessions                    List caller's sessions (paginated, with device metadata)\nGET    /auth/v1/sessions/current            Get current session details\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions/current            Logout (revoke current session)\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions/{id}              Revoke a specific other session\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions                    Revoke all OTHER sessions (keep current)\nDELETE /auth/v1/sessions?scope=all          Revoke ALL sessions including current (explicit)\n\nPOST   /auth/v1/register                    User registration (not session-modeled)\nPOST   /auth/v1/password/reset/request      Password reset initiation\nPOST   /auth/v1/password/reset/confirm      Password reset completion (rotates session)\nPOST   /auth/v1/email/verify                Email verification\n```\n\nSession token transport:\n- Web (BFF): HttpOnly `session` cookie, SameSite=Strict, Secure\n- Mobile: `Authorization: Bearer &lt;token&gt;` header\n- NestJS guard checks both; same lookup path (`hash(token) → sessions table`)\n\n---\n\n### Where Consensus Is Genuine vs Split\n\n| Topic | Consensus? | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| OIDC `POST /oauth/token` for federated login | Strong | Mandatory if supporting third-party OAuth2 clients |\n| Session listing with device metadata | Strong | Every mature platform has it |\n| `DELETE /sessions/{id}` for revoke-specific | Strong | Ory, Okta, Keycloak, Clerk all do this |\n| \"Revoke others, keep current\" semantic | Strong | Ory, Supabase, Better Auth all implement it |\n| Cookie vs Bearer dual-transport, same token | Strong | Ory Kratos is the canonical implementation |\n| Separate `/auth/v1` + `/api/v1` versioning | Strong | Supabase, Auth0, Okta do it |\n| `POST /sessions` vs `POST /login` for login | Split | Resource model wins in theory; RPC wins in practice |\n| `DELETE /sessions` = all vs all-except-current | Split | Depends on default behavior choice; document clearly |</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>99473</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>18</tool_uses><duration_ms>299004</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
