            "content": "## v0.1: Minimal Q&A harness\n\nThe smallest useful version: single-user, single-model **streaming** Q&A — no worker, no queue, no tools, no supervisor. Built per agents-best-practices (\"smallest reliable single-loop harness\"). Durable runs (v0.2) and governance (v0.3) come later.\n\n### Architecture overview\n\nA user message is answered by **one streaming model call**. A typed session/event model (#53) feeds a cache-aware context builder; a thin `ModelClient` (#54) calls one provider with the user's key; the loop (#55) streams and persists. Identity for that loop comes from `apps/api` itself: revocable server-side sessions (#60) give every request a trusted tenant id, and `apps/web` becomes a thin client of the API (#63) rather than owning the DB. Budgets + cost/cache telemetry (#56) wrap the loop, compaction (#57) keeps long chats in-window, and a minimal eval set (#58) gates release. The existing `langgraph-supervisor` chat path is replaced by this single-model loop.\n\n### Key design decisions\n\n- One streaming model call, **not** a supervisor graph (multi-agent deferred until evals justify it).\n- No worker/queue — stream directly from the API (the durable-run pipeline is the v0.2 upgrade).\n- `apps/api` is the **sole DB owner**; `apps/web` is a thin client that calls the API directly (no BFF/proxy in the default deploy). See SPEC.md §22.0.\n- Tenant identity is **server-derived** from a revocable session — never read from client input (closes the #61-class IDOR by construction).\n- Stable, cache-aware prompt prefix from turn one (cache hit rate is the cost floor).\n- One provider, user-supplied key, behind a `ModelClient` interface (full BYOK is v0.4).\n- Answer-only (Level 0/1) autonomy; tools/permissions arrive with later milestones.\n\n## Tracks\n\nv0.1 work is grouped into four tracks. **Persistence**, **Model**, and **Auth** are the foundations; the **Loop** track is the actual Q&A harness and depends on all three.\n\n### 🗃️ Pe