            "content": "# Spec — #63: `apps/web` → thin API client (remove DB + NextAuth-adapter)\n\n> Status: spec for review. Implements SPEC §22.0 (the canonical client/server boundary). Depends on #60 (`/auth/v1` + revocable sessions) and #55 (the streaming loop at `POST /api/v1/chats/:id/messages`), both merged.\n\n## 1. What this is (and is not)\n\nThis is a **client/integration cutover**, not a new agent harness. `apps/web` stops being a mini-backend (its own Postgres, Drizzle schema, NextAuth DrizzleAdapter + JWT sessions, and web-local `/api/v1` + langgraph-supervisor routes) and becomes a **thin client** that calls `apps/api` directly at a configurable `API_URL`. `apps/api` is the sole DB owner (SPEC §22.0); the browser is the API consumer; `apps/web` is **not** a BFF/proxy.\n\nThe mechanical half — deleting `lib/db`, the adapter, the JWT layer — is low-risk and skimmable. The half that earns the spec is:\n- **Contract reconciliation** between what the browser sends/expects today and what `apps/api` actually exposes (envelope shape, streaming request shape, chat-create-before-stream).\n- **The cross-origin auth boundary** — what deleting NextAuth costs (no more server-side `auth()`), and the layered, fail-closed auth-state model that replaces it.\n\nWrite and review this spec weighted accordingly.\n\n## 2. MVP scope, assumptions, non-goals\n\n**In scope**\n- Remove `apps/web/lib/db` (schema, queries, `db.ts`, `migrate.ts`, `drizzle.config.ts`, `migrations/`) and the NextAuth adapter/JWT wiring. `apps/web` holds **no** DB connection, ORM, schema, or auth adapter.\n- Rewire the **auth UI** (login/register/logout, sidebar user) to call `/auth/v1` directly with `credentials: 'include'`.\n- Rewire **chat list + chat streaming** to `apps/api`'s `/api/v1/chats` surface (including the #55 streaming endpoint).\n- Replace middleware auth with the §22.0 **layered auth-state model** (optimistic cookie-presence gate; `GET /auth/v1/me` as source of truth; client 401 interceptor).\n- Add the two **API-side enablers** that only matter once the browser calls api cross-origin: **CORS** (origin allowlist + credentials) and **cookie `Domain`** (set + cleared symmetrically).\n\n**Assumptions**\n- `apps/web` and `apps/api` are deployed under a **shared parent domain** (e.g. `app.<host>` + `api.<host>`) — i.e. **same-site**. This is what makes `SameSite=Lax` + `Domain=.<host>` sufficient for the cookie to ride cross-subdomain. A truly cross-site split (different registrable domains) is **out of scope** and would require `SameSite=None; Secure` and a stricter CORS posture — called out in §8.\n- `API_URL` is exposed to the browser as **`NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`** (public, not a secret — the browser makes the calls).\n- One model, one provider, server-resolved credential (#55 reality). The client does not choose the model for the loop.\n\n**Non-goals (tracked as separate issues, see §11)**\n- **No `GET /api/v1/models` endpoint on api.** The #55 loop ignores client model selection, so the web model-selector is *already decorative*. Web keeps a **static display list**; real \"models endpoint + wire selection into the loop\" is a separate issue.\n- **No chat title generation.** The legacy route titled chats via `title-generator.ts`; #55 persists `\"New chat\"`. Post-cutover, new chats stay `\"New chat\"` until a titling-on-api follow-up.\n- **No API client codegen.** Per `apps/api/CLAUDE.md`, SDK codegen off `openapi.json` is deferred post-v0.1. Web hand-writes a thin typed fetch layer (ky) against the known contract.\n- No projects/knowledge/connectors rewiring beyond what already calls the web DB.\n\n## 3. Architecture — the §22.0 client/server boundary\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    subgraph browser[\"Browser (apps/web — thin client)\"]\n        MW[\"middleware.ts<br/>optimistic cookie-presence gate\"]\n        UI[\"React UI<br/>login-form · chat page · sidebar\"]\n        QC[\"TanStack Query + ky<br/>useMe / useChats / useChat transport<br/>credentials: 'include'<br/>401 interceptor\"]\n    end\n\n    subgraph api[\"apps/api (NestJS — sole DB owner)\"]\n        AUTH[\"/auth/v1<br/>register · login · me · sessions · logout\"]\n        CHAT[\"/api/v1/chats<br/>list · create · :id/messages (SSE)\"]\n        GUARD[\"SessionAuthGuard<br/>(authoritative check)\"]\n        DB[(\"Postgres<br/>RLS-enforced\")]\n    end\n\n    UI --> QC\n    MW -. redirect on missing cookie .-> UI\n    QC -- \"Authorization / Cookie\" --> AUTH\n    QC -- \"Authorization / Cookie\" --> CHAT\n    AUTH --> GUARD\n    CHAT --> GUARD\n    GUARD --> DB\n```\n\n**Layered auth-state (the load-bearing design).** Three layers, each with a distinct job. Stated up front so no one mistakes the middleware for the security boundary:\n\n| Layer | Runs where | Checks | Authority | On failure |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1. Middleware gate | Edge/Node, pre-render | Cookie **presence only** (no DB, no api call) | **UX only — not security** | Redirect to `/login?callbackUrl=…` |\n| 2. API guard (`SessionAuthGuard`) | `apps/api`, per request | Token validity, session not revoked/expired | **Authoritative** | `401` |\n| 3. Client 401 interceptor | Browser, on any api response | Catches revocation/expiry mid-session | Reactive | Clear query cache → redirect to `/login` |\n\n`GET /auth/v1/me` is the **source of truth** for \"am I really logged in + who am I\" (TanStack Query, `useMe()`). The middleware can be fooled by a forged/expired cookie — that request renders the page optimistically, then **fails at layer 2** and is caught at layer 3. This is intentional and consistent with the project security principles: *fail closed* (the guard denies when identity is absent/invalid), and *don't treat a UX redirect as a mitigation* — the api guard is the only thing that gates data.\n\n## 4. Cutover surface — remove / rewire / add\n\n### 4a. Remove (dead once the adapter + route are gone)\n\n| Path | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `lib/db/**` (schema, queries, `db.ts`, `migrate.ts`, `drizzle.config.ts`, `migrations/`) | api is sole DB owner |\n| `app/(auth)/auth.ts`, `app/(auth)/auth.config.ts` | NextAuth instance + DrizzleAdapter |\n| `app/(auth)/actions.ts` | server action calling next-auth `signIn` |\n| `app/(auth)/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts` | NextAuth handlers |\n| `app/(auth)/api/auth/register/route.ts` | web-local register against web DB |\n| `app/(chat)/api/v1/chats/route.ts` | langgraph-supervisor chat backend (replaced by #55) |\n| `app/(models)/api/v1/models/route.tsx` | web-local models route |\n| **Orphaned by the above** (per the orphan-cleanup rule): `lib/ai/experts/**`, `lib/ai/providers.ts`, most of `lib/ai/models.ts` (keep only a static display list, drop `instance`/provider machinery), `lib/services/chat/title-generator.ts`, `utils/stream-logging.ts` | only referenced by the deleted route/adapter |\n\n### 4b. Rewire\n\n| Path | Today | After |\n|---|---|---|\n| `middleware.ts` | `auth((req)=>…)` reads `req.auth` (DB-backed JWT) | Read session cookie **presence** only; same redirect logic; **no** `next-auth` import |\n| `app/layout.tsx` | `await auth()` + `<SessionProvider>` (next-auth/react) | Drop both; provide a `useMe()`-backed auth context via TanStack Query |\n| `app/(auth)/login/components/login-form.tsx` | `signIn` (next-auth/react) → server action | `POST ${API_URL}/auth/v1/login` (ky, `credentials:'include'`) → on 200, invalidate `me` + redirect |\n| `app/(auth)/register/page.tsx` | web register route | `POST ${API_URL}/auth/v1/register` |\n| `app/(chat)/components/app-sidebar/app-sidebar-user.tsx` | `useSession()` | `useMe()` (TanStack Query on `/auth/v1/me`) |\n| `lib/services/chat/queries.ts` | `ky.get(\"/api/v1/chats\")` expecting `{data: ChatResponse[]}` | `ky.get(\\`${API_URL}/api/v1/chats\\`, {credentials:'include'})` returning a **bare array** (drop `.data`); align `ChatResponse` field names to api (`updatedAt`, no `lastMessageAt`) |\n| `lib/services/models/queries.ts` | `ky.get(\"/api/v1/models\")` | Return a **static** model list (no api call); type no longer imported from a route |\n| `app/(chat)/page.tsx` | `useChat` transport → web langgraph route | `useChat` transport → #55 endpoint (see §5c) |\n| `contexts/chat-context.tsx`, `components/ai/model-preview-card.tsx` | import `ChatModelResponse` from the models route | import from the static models module |\n\n### 4c. Add (API-side enablers — `apps/api`)\n\n| Change | File | Detail |\n|---|---|---|\n| CORS | `apps/api/src/app.setup.ts` (`configureApp`) | `app.enableCors({ origin: <web origin allowlist, config-driven>, credentials: true })`. Without it the browser is rejected at preflight. Allowlist from env (e.g. `WEB_ORIGIN`), **not** `*` (incompatible with `credentials`). |\n| Cookie `Domain` (set) | `apps/api/src/auth/auth.controller.ts` (`setSessionCookie`) | Add `domain: <SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN>` (config-driven, e.g. `.<host>`) so the cookie is sent to `api.<host>` and readable by web middleware. |\n| Cookie `Domain` (clear) | same file (`clearSessionCookie`) | **Must** pass the identical `domain` — otherwise logout / \"sign out everywhere\" won't clear the cross-subdomain cookie. Latent-bug twin of the set path. |\n\n## 5. The three intricate interactions (specify step-by-step)\n\n### 5a. Auth flow (login)\n1. User submits login-form → `POST ${API_URL}/auth/v1/login` with `{email, password}`, `credentials:'include'`.\n2. api validates, creates a server-side session, returns `AuthTokenResponse {token, user, session}` **and** `Set-Cookie` (httpOnly, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure`, `Domain=.<host>`, `expires`).\n3. Browser stores the cookie automatically. Web **ignores** the `token` in the body for cookie-mode (cookie is the credential); it may seed the `me` query cache from `user`.\n4. Web invalidates/refetches `useMe()` and redirects to `callbackUrl ?? \"/\"`.\n\n(Register is identical against `/auth/v1/register`, 201.)\n\n### 5b. Layered auth-state at render\n1. Navigation to a gated path → **middleware** checks cookie presence. Absent → redirect to `/login`. Present → allow render (optimistic).\n2. Page renders assuming authed; `useMe()` fires `GET /auth/v1/me` with `credentials:'include'`.\n3. `me` 200 → render user. `me` 401 (forged/expired/revoked cookie passed middleware) → **client 401 interceptor** clears cache + redirects to `/login`. This is the only place a stale cookie is caught for read pages.\n\n### 5c. Chat create → stream (the single most intricate interaction)\n\nThe legacy route auto-created a chat on first POST. **#55 hard-404s on a missing chat, and `POST /api/v1/chats` (CreateChatDto) does not accept a client-supplied id.** So ai-chatbot's \"generate UUID client-side, navigate optimistically, route upserts\" is **unavailable**. v0.1 default = **create-then-stream round-trip**:\n\n1. **First message in a new chat:** `POST ${API_URL}/api/v1/chats` `{title?}` → returns `ChatResponse {id, …}`.\n2. Navigate/set active chat to that `id` (this instantiates the chat hook for that `id`).\n3. The chat hook's transport URL is **`${API_URL}/api/v1/chats/${id}/messages`** (chatId baked into the *static* `api`, because llame puts chatId in the **path**; see §6/divergence).\n4. `sendMessage` → `useChat` `DefaultChatTransport` with `prepareSendMessagesRequest` reshaping the body to **`{ message: <lastMessage{id,parts}> }`** (only the new message; history is server-side per #55) and setting `credentials:'include'`.\n5. api streams the AI-SDK v5 **UI-message SSE** (`toUIMessageStreamResponse()`); `useChat` consumes it natively (producer/consumer already match — the only client work is the reshape + credentials).\n6. Subsequent messages in an existing chat skip step 1–2.\n\n> First-message latency cost = one extra round-trip. Accepted for v0.1. Alternative (accept optional `id` on the create endpoint to restore optimistic-navigate) is the recommended **future** upgrade — see §9.\n\n## 6. Hard requirements\n\n- **R1 — no DB in web.** `apps/web` has no Postgres connection, Drizzle, schema, migrations, or NextAuth adapter. `grep` for `lib/db`, `drizzle`, `DrizzleAdapter`, `next-auth` returns zero live references.\n- **R2 — direct api calls.** All auth and chat/domain reads/writes go to `apps/api` at `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`; web never proxies them through its own route handlers.\n- **R3 — credentials on every cross-origin call.** Every browser→api request (ky + the `useChat` transport) sends `credentials:'include'`.\n- **R4 — layered gate.** Middleware checks cookie presence only (no DB, no per-request api call); `GET /auth/v1/me` is the authed-state source of truth; a 401 interceptor handles mid-session revocation.\n- **R5 — middleware is not the security boundary.** No code or comment implies the middleware authorizes data access; the api guard is authoritative. (Stated to satisfy the \"a code comment is not a mitigation / fail closed\" principle.)\n- **R6 — CORS + cookie Domain.** api sets a config-driven origin allowlist with `credentials:true` (never `*`), and sets **and clears** the session cookie with the same `Domain`.\n- **R7 — streaming contract.** The chat transport posts `{message:{id,parts}}` to `/api/v1/chats/:id/messages`; the new message id is a client-generated UUID (idempotency key per #55).\n- **R8 — create-before-stream.** A new chat is created via `POST /api/v1/chats` before the first message stream; no reliance on api upserting an unknown chat id.\n- **R9 — envelope alignment.** Web consumes api's response shapes verbatim (chat list = bare array, not `{data:[]}`); no shape is changed on the api side for #63.\n- **R10 — no secret leakage.** `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` is the only api coordinate exposed to the browser; no provider keys, session secrets, or DB URLs exist in `apps/web` config.\n\n## 7. Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `apps/web` has no DB connection / ORM / schema / auth-adapter (R1); build passes with `lib/db` and `next-auth` removed.\n- [ ] Login, register, logout, \"sign out everywhere\" go through `/auth/v1` with `credentials:'include'`; the session cookie is set and cleared with matching `Domain`.\n- [ ] Chat list + chat streaming go through `/api/v1`; web never queries Postgres; the chat page streams a #55 response end-to-end.\n- [ ] Page-gating uses middleware cookie-presence + `/auth/v1/me`; a **revoked session** is rejected on the next read (manual: revoke via `/auth/v1/sessions`, confirm the next `me`/chat call 401s and the client redirects).\n- [ ] CORS preflight succeeds from the web origin and is **rejected** from a disallowed origin (negative test).\n- [ ] **Negative auth test:** a request with no cookie / a forged cookie reaches the api guard and gets `401` (never silently authorized by middleware).\n\n## 8. Security & threat considerations\n\n- **Cross-origin cookie boundary.** The whole flow rests on the same-site assumption (§2): `SameSite=Lax` + `Domain=.<host>` lets the cookie ride to `api.<host>` on top-level navigation and same-site fetches. **If web and api are ever split across registrable domains, this breaks** and requires `SameSite=None; Secure` + a tightened CORS allowlist + CSRF consideration. State the deployment assumption in the env docs; fail closed if `SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN`/`WEB_ORIGIN` are unset in production rather than silently widening.\n- **CORS allowlist, never `*`.** `credentials:true` is incompatible with a wildcard origin; the allowlist is explicit and config-driven. An over-broad allowlist is a tenant-isolation risk (a malicious origin could ride the user's cookie) — keep it to known web origins.\n- **Middleware ≠ guard (fail closed).** The middleware's optimistic check must never be the only thing between a request and tenant data. The api `SessionAuthGuard` (already authoritative, server-derived identity per #60) is the boundary; #63 must not introduce any web surface that reads tenant data without going through it.\n- **No new reachable-but-unsecured surface.** #63 removes web routes; it must not add a web route that touches data. (It doesn't — the browser calls api directly.)\n- **Secrets.** Deleting `lib/db` and the adapter removes the web-side `DATABASE_URL` and any provider keys from web config (BYOK keys are api/user-owned). Confirm none linger in `.env`/`next.config`.\n\n## 9. Open decisions (with recommended defaults)\n\n1. **Chat creation (G4).** *Recommended: (a) create-then-stream round-trip* — smaller cut, no api change, one-time first-message latency. Alternative (b): accept an optional client-supplied `id` on `POST /api/v1/chats` to restore ai-chatbot-style optimistic navigation — cleaner UX but expands #63 into an api change. Ship (a) now; track (b) as the UX upgrade.\n2. **Models (G1).** *Recommended: inline a static display list in web* and state that model selection is currently a **no-op** for the loop (the #55 loop resolves one credential server-side and ignores the client's choice). Do **not** build `GET /api/v1/models` in #63. Track \"real models endpoint + wire selection into the loop\" as a separate issue.\n\nBoth are presented as decisions-with-defaults, not blockers — implementation can proceed on the recommended path unless overridden.\n\n## 10. Verification against librarized personal assistants\n\nPrimary reference: **vercel/ai-chatbot** (our exact stack — Next.js 15 + AI SDK v5 + Drizzle). Position: a **partial** reference, because ai-chatbot keeps NextAuth **in-app** with its own DB — #63 deliberately **diverges** by moving auth *out* to `apps/api`. So ai-chatbot validates the *streaming-consumption* mechanics but **not** the auth topology.\n\n| Concern | ai-chatbot | llame #63 | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Chat stream consumption | `useChat` + `DefaultChatTransport` consuming a UI-message SSE stream | identical | ✅ direct match — #55 returns `toUIMessageStreamResponse()`, consumed natively |\n| Send only the last message | `prepareSendMessagesRequest` → `{ id, message: lastMessage, … }` | `prepareSendMessagesRequest` → `{ message: lastMessage }` | ✅ same pattern (reshape body + history server-side) |\n| chatId location | in the **body** (`id`), so transport `api` stays static `/api/chat` | in the **path** (`/api/v1/chats/:id/messages`) | ⚠️ **divergence** — bake chatId into the per-chat static transport URL; do **not** rely on `prepareSendMessagesRequest` overriding `api` (unverified SDK capability) |\n| First-message chat creation | client-gen UUID + optimistic navigate + route upsert | create-then-stream round-trip (api 404s on unknown id; create rejects client id) | ⚠️ **can't port** — see §5c / §9 |\n| Cross-origin credentials | same-origin (no `credentials:'include'`) | cross-subdomain → `credentials:'include'` everywhere | ⚠️ llame-specific |\n| Auth gating | NextAuth in-app; current versions gate in server components/route handlers via `auth()` (no root `middleware.ts` in the checkout) | auth in `apps/api`; web uses the §22.0 layered cookie-presence + `/auth/v1/me` model | ⚠️ **divergence** — ai-chatbot is *not* a reference for the middleware-cookie-gate; this is llame's own design |\n\n**Deferred-complexity references** (consulted, not adopted for #63): **hermes-agent** (server-derived canonical identity — conceptually aligns with api-owned identity, but its session-lineage/identity-mapping machinery is beyond a thin-client cutover) and **openclaw** (multi-channel routing — relevant when Telegram/Discord clients also call `apps/api` directly; #63 establishes the boundary that makes those additional thin clients possible, but ships only the web client).\n\nNet: the **streaming half** is a verified copy of ai-chatbot with two path/credentials deltas; the **auth half** is a deliberate, documented divergence (auth lives in api, web is thin) with no clean in-stack reference — which is exactly why the layered model is specified explicitly here.\n\n## 11. Minimal implementation path\n\n1. **API enablers first** (unblocks the browser): CORS allowlist + cookie `Domain` (set **and** clear) in `apps/api`. Verify preflight + a manual cross-origin `me` call.\n2. **Auth UI cutover:** delete NextAuth (`auth.ts`, `auth.config.ts`, `actions.ts`, the two `(auth)/api/auth/*` routes); rewire login-form/register to `/auth/v1`; add `useMe()` + the TanStack Query auth context; replace `SessionProvider` in `layout.tsx`; rewire sidebar `useSession`.\n3. **Middleware:** rewrite to cookie-presence gate (drop `next-auth`).\n4. **Chat list:** repoint `lib/services/chat/queries.ts` to `${API_URL}/api/v1/chats` (bare array, `credentials:'include'`); align `ChatResponse`.\n5. **Chat stream:** rewire `(chat)/page.tsx` transport to #55 (create-then-stream §5c).\n6. **Models:** static list; mark selection no-op.\n7. **Delete the rest** (`lib/db/**`, web `/api/v1/*` routes, orphaned `lib/ai/**` + `title-generator` + `stream-logging`).\n8. **Verify:** `pnpm --filter web build` + `lint`; manual end-to-end (login → create chat → stream → logout → revoked-session 401); CORS negative test.\n\n## 12. Dependencies & tracked follow-ups\n\n- **Depends on:** #60 (`/auth/v1` + sessions), #55 (streaming loop). Both merged.\n- **Spawns (track as new issues, link in #51):**\n  - Real `GET /api/v1/models` endpoint + wire model selection into the loop (G1).\n  - Optional client-supplied chat `id` on create → optimistic navigation (G4 option b).\n  - Chat title generation on api (regression from deleting `title-generator.ts`).\n  - (If a cross-site deploy is ever targeted) `SameSite=None` + CSRF posture.\n",
